<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Baxter%20SL"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Sally L Baxter</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>2,</sup><sup>3</sup>, <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Freeman%20WR"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id5"><span class="name western">William R Freeman</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id5">
<h3>
<span class="name western">William R Freeman</span>, <span class="degrees">MD</span>
</h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>1</sup>Jacobs Retina Center, University of California San Diego, La Jolla, California, United States of America, 92037</div>
<div class="p">
<sup>2</sup>Shiley Eye Institute, University of California San Diego, La Jolla, California, United States of America, 92037</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Freeman%20WR"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">William R Freeman</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>1,</sup><sup>2</sup>, <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Borooah%20S"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id6"><span class="name western">Shyamanga Borooah</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id6">
<h3>
<span class="name western">Shyamanga Borooah</span>, <span class="degrees">MBBS, PhD</span>
</h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>1</sup>Jacobs Retina Center, University of California San Diego, La Jolla, California, United States of America, 92037</div>
<div class="p">
<sup>2</sup>Shiley Eye Institute, University of California San Diego, La Jolla, California, United States of America, 92037</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Borooah%20S"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Shyamanga Borooah</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>1,</sup><sup>2</sup>
</div>
<ul class="d-buttons inline-list">
<li><button class="d-button" aria-controls="aip_a" aria-expanded="false">Author information</button></li>
<li><button class="d-button" aria-controls="clp_a" aria-expanded="false">Copyright and License information</button></li>
</ul>
<div class="d-panels font-secondary-light">
<div id="aip_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none">
<div class="p" id="A1">
<sup>1</sup>Jacobs Retina Center, University of California San Diego, La Jolla, California, United States of America, 92037</div>
<div id="A2">
<sup>2</sup>Shiley Eye Institute, University of California San Diego, La Jolla, California, United States of America, 92037</div>
<div id="A3">
<sup>3</sup>Health Department of Biomedical Informatics, University of California San Diego, La Jolla, California, United States of America, 92037</div>
<div class="author-notes p"><div class="fn" id="CR1">
<sup>✉</sup><p class="display-inline"><strong>Corresponding author</strong>:Dr. Shyamanga Borooah, Assistant Professor, Retinal division, Shiley Eye Institute, University of California San Diego, 9415 Gilman Drive, La Jolla, CA 92093, United States of America, <span>sborooah@health.ucsd.edu</span></p>
</div></div>
</div>
<div id="clp_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none"><div class="p"><a href="/about/copyright/" class="usa-link">PMC Copyright notice</a></div></div>
</div>
<div>PMCID: PMC13001792  NIHMSID: NIHMS1902694  PMID: <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37229759/" class="usa-link">37229759</a>
</div>
<div class="ra xbox p" role="complementary" aria-label="Related or updated information about this article"><div>The publisher's version of this article is available at <a href="https://doi.org/10.1097/IAE.0000000000003844" class="usa-link usa-link--external" data-ga-action="click_feat_suppl" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Retina</a>
</div></div>
</div></section></section><section aria-label="Article content"><section class="body main-article-body"><section class="abstract" id="ABS1"><h2>Abstract</h2>
<section id="S1"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Purpose:</h3>
<p id="P1">To refine the retinal phenotypes of suspected pentosan polysulfate sodium toxicity using ultra-widefield imaging.</p></section><section id="S2"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Methods:</h3>
<p id="P2">Patients with complete dosing profiles who visited the ophthalmology department and with ultra-widefield and optical coherence tomography imaging records were identified using electronic health records at a large academic center. Retinal toxicity was initially identified using previously published imaging criteria, while grading was categorized using both previously reported and new classification systems.</p></section><section id="S3"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Results:</h3>
<p id="P3">One hundred and four patients were included in the study. Twenty-six (25%) were identified as having toxicity from PPS. The mean duration of exposure and cumulative dose between the retinopathy group (162.7 months, 1803.2 grams) were longer and higher compared to the non-retinopathy group (69.7 months, 972.6 grams) (both <em>p</em>&lt;0.001). There was variability of extra-macular phenotype in the retinopathy group, with four eyes having only peripapillary involvement and six eyes having far peripheral extension.</p></section><section id="S4"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Conclusion:</h3>
<p id="P4">Retinal toxicity in the setting of prolonged exposure and increased cumulative dosing from PPS therapy produces phenotypic variability. Providers should be aware of the extramacular component of toxicity when screening patients. Understanding the different retinal phenotypes may prevent continued exposure and reduce the risk of vision-threatening foveal involving disease.</p></section><section id="kwd-group1" class="kwd-group"><p><strong>Keywords:</strong> Adverse drug reaction, drug toxicity, elmiron, pentosan polysulfate sodium, pigmentary retinopathy</p></section></section><section id="S5"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">INTRODUCTION</h2>
<p id="P5">Pentosan polysulfate sodium (PPS) is a semi-synthetic, sulfated polysaccharide that is used to relieve discomfort associated with interstitial cystitis (IC).<sup><a href="#R1" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R1">1</a></sup> In 2018, Pearce and colleagues initially described pigmentary maculopathy in the setting of chronic PPS exposure, which they called PPS maculopathy.<sup><a href="#R2" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R2">2</a></sup> Its prevalence has been reported to range from 16–23.1%, varying by institution.<sup><a href="#R3" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R3">3</a>–<a href="#R5" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R5">5</a></sup> Several studies have described the PPS macular toxicity phenotypic characteristics using various imaging modalities.<sup><a href="#R3" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R3">3</a>,<a href="#R4" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R4">4</a>,<a href="#R6" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R6">6</a>–<a href="#R8" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R8">8</a></sup> However, consensus imaging criteria have yet to be established.</p>
<p id="P6">The purpose of this study was to identify patients with a history of exposure to PPS and to further refine the phenotype for PPS retinopathy, particularly focusing on the extra-macular retinal findings. Because urologists at our academic center were the first to trial, patent, and prescribe PPS for interstitial cystitis<sup><a href="#R9" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R9">9</a></sup>, our group aimed to study a relatively large cohort of patients with long-term PPS use at a single center.</p></section><section id="S6"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">METHODS</h2>
<p id="P7">This retrospective review was approved by the Institutional Review Board of the University of California San Diego (UCSD) and adhered to the tenets of the Declaration of Helsinki. This study complied with the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act of 1996, with all data being anonymized. Informed consent was provided as per institution protocol.</p>
<section id="S7"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Data Source and Patient Selection</h3>
<p id="P8">Patients were initially identified using structured queries of the UCSD electronic health record (EHR) data warehouse (Epic SlicerDicer; Verona, WI, USA). Patients with “outpatient medications”, “medications”, or “hospital or clinic-administered medications” of pentosan polysulfate sodium were queried. The cohort was then limited to those who visited the Ophthalmology department (Shiley Eye Institute) from January 1, 2016 until December 16, 2022 who underwent retinal imaging in one or both eyes. The start date was chosen as this was when ultra-widefield (UWF) imaging became available at our institution.</p></section><section id="S8"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">EHR case review and Retinal imaging review</h3>
<p id="P9">Chart review included recording demographic characteristics, weight (in kg), reason for eye visit, and dosing and duration of PPS therapy. Patients with UWF pseudocolor, UWF fundus autofluorescence (FAF), near-infrared reflectance (NIR), and spectral-domain optical coherence tomography (SD-OCT) were included, and two retinal specialists (FK, SB) reviewed individual retinal imaging available. Pseudocolor and FAF imaging was obtained using the UWF Optos California P200DTx (Optos plc, Dunfermline, UK). NIR and SD-OCT imaging was obtained using the Heidelberg HRA+OCT Spectralis System (Heidelberg Engineering, Heidelberg, Germany).</p></section><section id="S9"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">PPS Retinopathy Diagnosis, Grading Severity, and Classification</h3>
<p id="P10">A diagnosis of PPS retinopathy was based on multimodal imaging findings described from prior publications showing irregular autofluorescence (FAF) and reflectance (NIR) pattern with corresponding nodular excrescences at the level of the retinal pigment epithelium (RPE) (macular SD-OCT).<sup><a href="#R2" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R2">2</a>,<a href="#R6" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R6">6</a></sup> Retinal imaging was graded using previously published criteria described by Hanif et al.<sup><a href="#R6" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R6">6</a></sup> and Wang et al.<sup><a href="#R3" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R3">3</a></sup> (see <a href="#T1" class="usa-link">Table 1</a> for details of criteria). Review of imaging conducted by the imaging graders identified extra-macular characteristics of potential retinal toxicity. Hence, in addition to the two previous criteria, our group developed a further classification system with slight differences from the previous grading systems in order to encompass extra-macular findings which were observed when using UWF imaging in review of our cases. This classification system was based on characteristics of the lesion, lesion location, extent of the lesion, and the presence or absence of atrophy seen on UWF FAF, NIR, and macular SD-OCT. To make the ordinal variables uniform for both grading severity systems, our group replaced the grading severity by Wang et al. with Arabic numerical ranking (i.e., Mild – 1, Moderate – 2, Severe – 3). The classification provided by our group was illustrated as Roman numerals (I, II, III). (<a href="#T1" class="usa-link">Table 1</a>, <a href="#F1" class="usa-link">Figure 1</a>)</p>
<section class="tw xbox font-sm" id="T1"><h4 class="obj_head">Table 1.</h4>
<div class="caption p"><p id="P24">Disease grading severity and classification system of pentosan polysulfate sodium retinopathy</p></div>
<div class="tbl-box p" tabindex="0"><table class="content" frame="box" rules="all">
<colgroup span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
</colgroup>
<thead><tr>
<th align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1"></th>
<th align="left" valign="middle" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Hanif, et al. grading<a href="#TFN1" class="usa-link"><sup>*</sup></a>
</th>
<th align="left" valign="middle" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Wang, et al. grading<a href="#TFN2" class="usa-link"><sup>†</sup></a>
</th>
<th colspan="3" align="left" valign="middle" rowspan="1">Our classification</th>
</tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Grading Severity</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">1</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Mild (1)</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">IA</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">IB</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">IC</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td rowspan="2" align="left" valign="top" colspan="1">Definition</td>
<td rowspan="2" align="left" valign="top" colspan="1">Findings contained within the vascular arcades without atrophy</td>
<td rowspan="2" align="left" valign="top" colspan="1">Presence of a speckled pattern of hypo- and hyperautofluorescence on FAF (or only hyperautofluorescent lesions) and no evidence of well-demarcated atrophic lesions on FAF and no evidence of cRORA<a href="#TFN1" class="usa-link"><sup>*</sup></a> with SD-OCT</td>
<td colspan="3" align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1">FAF (NIR): array of hyperautofluorescent (hyperreflective) and hypoautofluorescent (hyporeflective) spots contained</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">In the macula</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">In the peripapillary area</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">In both the macula and peripapillary area</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Grading Severity</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">2</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Moderate (2)</td>
<td colspan="3" align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1">II</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Definition</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Findings extending to the temporal vascular arcades but not spanning 2 disc diameters beyond the arcades and/or presence of noncentral atrophy</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Presence of well-demarcated, nummular, hypoautofluorescent atrophic lesions on FAF that colocalized with cRORA<a href="#TFN1" class="usa-link"><sup>*</sup></a> on SD-OCT within the macula but without central foveal involvement</td>
<td colspan="3" align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1">FAF (NIR): densely packed “plaque-like” pattern of hyperautofluorescent (hyperreflective) and hypoautofluorescent (hyporeflective) spots in the macula (with or without the peripapillary area), extending to the midperiphery</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Grading Severity</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">3</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Severe (3)</td>
<td colspan="3" align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1">III</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Definition</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Findings extending at least 2 disc diameters beyond the temporal vascular arcades and/or presence of atrophy involving the foveal center</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Presence of hypoautofluorescent atrophy within the macula with colocalization with cRORA<a href="#TFN3" class="usa-link"><sup>‡</sup></a> with SD-OCT and involving the central fovea</td>
<td colspan="3" align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1">FAF: densely packed “plaque-like” pattern of hyperautofluorescent and hypoautofluorescent spots in the macula and peripapillary area with extension to the retinal far periphery</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Additional finding</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1"></td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1"></td>
<td colspan="3" align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1">An addition of “a” after any grading severity indicates the presence of atrophy of any size seen in both FAF and SD-OCT.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="table/T1/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<div class="tw-foot p">
<div class="fn" id="TFN1">
<sup>*</sup><p class="display-inline" id="P25">- grading severity adapted from the study by Hanif et al.<sup><a href="#R6" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R6">6</a></sup></p>
</div>
<div class="fn" id="TFN2">
<sup>†</sup><p class="display-inline" id="P26">- grading severity adapted from the study by Wang et al.<sup><a href="#R3" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R3">3</a></sup></p>
</div>
<div class="fn" id="TFN3">
<sup>‡</sup><p class="display-inline" id="P27">complete retinal pigment epithelial and outer retinal atrophy (cRORA) is defined as a continuous band of hypertransmission at least 250 μm in diameter, a continuous zone of retinal pigment epithelial attenuation or disruption at least 250 μm in diameter, and superimposed photoreceptor degeneration</p>
</div>
<div class="fn" id="TFN4"><p id="P28">FAF – fundus autofluorescence; NIR – near-infrared reflectance; SD-OCT – spectral-domain optical coherence tomography</p></div>
</div></section><figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="F1"><h4 class="obj_head">Figure 1.</h4>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><a class="tileshop" target="_blank" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/core/lw/2.0/html/tileshop_pmc/tileshop_pmc_inline.html?title=Click%20on%20image%20to%20zoom&amp;p=PMC3&amp;id=13001792_nihms-1902694-f0001.jpg"><img class="graphic zoom-in" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/3f2f/13001792/01d2833966e7/nihms-1902694-f0001.jpg" loading="lazy" height="438" width="1050" alt="Figure 1."></a></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/F1/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p id="P22">A representative sample from our cohort showing the classification our group implemented. Each letter corresponds to both eyes of each patient. (A) Class IA – array of hyperautofluorescent or hyperreflective and hypoautofluorescent or hyporeflective spots in the macula, (B) Class IB – array of hyperautofluorescent or hyperreflective and hypoautofluorescent or hyporeflective spots in the peripapillary area (arrows), (C) Class IC – array of hyperautofluorescent or hyperreflective and hypoautofluorescent or hyporeflective spots in both the macula and peripapillary area (arrows), (D) Class II – densely packed “plaque-like” pattern of hyperautofluorescent and hypoautofluorescent spots in the macula (with or without the peripapillary area), extending to the midperiphery, (E) Class III – densely packed “plaque-like” pattern of hyperautofluorescent and hypoautofluorescent spots in the macula and peripapillary area with extension to the retinal far periphery.</p></figcaption></figure></section><section id="S10"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Statistical Analysis</h3>
<p id="P11">Subject level clinical and demographic characteristics were compared between cohorts using two-sample t-tests and Fisher’s Exact test for continuous and categorical variables, respectively. The normality of data was assessed through Shapiro-Wilk’s test, and Mann Whitney U tests were also considered for comparisons of continuous variables that did not meet all parametric assumptions. Statistical analyses were performed using the R programming language version 4.2.1 (R Foundation for Statistical Computing, Vienna, Austria). A p-value ≤ 0.05 was considered statistically significant.</p></section></section><section id="S11"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">RESULTS</h2>
<p id="P12">A total of 128 patients were identified as using PPS with retinal imaging performed. Upon review of our records, 11 subjects had incomplete dosing profiles, and 13 subjects did not have both SD-OCT and UWF imaging performed on the same day, and hence were excluded. Of the 104 subjects included in the study, 26 were identified as having PPS retinopathy (25%, <a href="#F2" class="usa-link">Figure 2</a>) using our classification.</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="F2"><h3 class="obj_head">Figure 2.</h3>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><a class="tileshop" target="_blank" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/core/lw/2.0/html/tileshop_pmc/tileshop_pmc_inline.html?title=Click%20on%20image%20to%20zoom&amp;p=PMC3&amp;id=13001792_nihms-1902694-f0002.jpg"><img class="graphic zoom-in" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/3f2f/13001792/1818e9a77012/nihms-1902694-f0002.jpg" loading="lazy" height="587" width="1050" alt="Figure 2."></a></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/F2/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p id="P23">Fundus autofluorescence, Near-infrared reflectance, and Spectral-domain optical coherence tomography of all suspected pentosan polysulfate sodium retinopathy patients. A to Z corresponds numerically to patient number 1 until 26</p></figcaption></figure><p id="P13">The most common reasons for eye care visits in the PPS retinopathy group and the non-retinopathy group were worsening of vision and asymptomatic screening for PPS retinopathy (57% and 26%, respectively for retinopathy group and 44% and 40%, respectively for non-retinopathy group).</p>
<p id="P14"><a href="#T2" class="usa-link">Table 2</a> shows the demographic and clinical characteristics of patients included in our cohort. The age, sex, race, ethnicity, and weight were not statistically significantly different between the PPS retinopathy and non-retinopathy groups (<em>p</em> = 0.053, 0.81, 0.16, 0.99, 0.66, respectively). The PPS retinopathy group had a statistically significantly greater mean duration of exposure of 162.7 months with a mean cumulative dosage of 1803.2 grams (vs. 69.7 months and 972.6 grams in the non-retinopathy ici group, both <em>p</em> &lt; 0.001). Age-adjusted comparison of duration of exposure and cumulative dose still showed a statistically significant difference (<em>p</em> &lt; 0.001).</p>
