<div class="fn" id="TFN5">
<sup>*</sup><p class="display-inline" id="P30">bold <em>p</em>-values denote statistical significance of less than 0.05.</p>
</div>
<div class="fn" id="TFN6"><p id="P31">PPS – Pentosan polysulfate sodium</p></div>
</div></section><p id="P15"><a href="#T3" class="usa-link">Table 3</a> shows the different grading severity and classification seen in our cohort. Previous grading systems<sup><a href="#R3" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R3">3</a>,<a href="#R6" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R6">6</a></sup> had identified outer retinal atrophy as an important severity criterion, on top of the extent of lesions within the macular region. Multimodal imaging among the PPS retinopathy group showed grading severity and classification variability. <a href="#T4" class="usa-link">Table 4</a> shows the distribution of the different retinopathy from our classification system. Twenty-nine eyes of sixteen patients were identified as Class I; 12 eyes of six patients involved only the macula (IA), four eyes of three patients involved only the peripapillary area (IB), and 13 eyes of seven patients involved both the macula and peripapillary area (IC). Thirteen eyes of seven patients were identified with plaque-like pattern of hyper- and hypoautofluorescence using FAF and irregular reflectivity patterns seen in NIR in the macula extending to the mid-periphery (II), while six eyes of three patients showed extension of this plaque-like pattern up to the far periphery (III). The age, race, sex, duration of exposure, and cumulative dose were not statistically significantly different among the classifications (<em>p</em> = 0.302, 0.512, 0.839, 0.234, and 0.094, respectively). Atrophy appeared to be distributed across different classifications (IAa [4 eyes], Ia [6 eyes], IIIa [1 eye]). A sub-analysis comparing the patients’ eyes with atrophy and those without in terms of duration of exposure and cumulative dose showed no statistically significant difference between the two groups (<a href="#SD1" class="usa-link">Table S1</a>). One patient was identified as having choroidal neovascularization and was treated with multiple intravitreal anti-vascular endothelial growth factor injections. The fellow eye of this patient, however, presented with retinopathy characteristic of PPS toxicity. The fellow eyes of two patients were noted to have vitelliform changes in the subfoveal region, and one eye of one patient was noted to have multiple areas of hyperreflective nodular RPE detachment.</p>
<section class="tw xbox font-sm" id="T3"><h3 class="obj_head">Table 3.</h3>
<div class="caption p"><p id="P32">Demographic information, exposure to medication, and disease staging and classification system in all patients with suspected pentosan polysulfate sodium retinopathy.</p></div>
<div class="tbl-box p" tabindex="0"><table class="content" frame="box" rules="all">
<colgroup span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
</colgroup>
<thead><tr>
<th align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Patient No.</th>
<th align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Age/Sex/Race</th>
<th align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Duration of exposure (months)</th>
<th align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Cumulative dose (grams)</th>
<th align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Laterality</th>
