<div class="tw-foot p"><div class="fn" id="TFN13">
<sup>*</sup><p class="display-inline" id="P40">Class 1 had been condensed summing all patients with IA, IB, and IC.</p>
</div></div></section></section><section id="S12"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">DISCUSSION</h2>
<p id="P16">This review of patients taking PPS seen in the ophthalmology department of a large academic center and having retinal imaging available for analysis identified 25% of the cohort having PPS toxicity. A strong correlation was found with cumulative dosing over 1500 grams, which is similar to that found in other recently published studies.<sup><a href="#R3" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R3">3</a>,<a href="#R5" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R5">5</a></sup> Our group also noted a statistically significant difference in duration of exposure (in months) to PPS between the retinopathy and non-retinopathy groups, suggesting that this was also risk factor. This may suggest that guidelines to limit the length of exposure may also help reduce the risk of PPS retinal toxicity.</p>
<p id="P17">We identified many patients with extra macular findings and generated a classification system to encompass these findings in order to help refine the phenotypic spectrum of PPS toxicity. Identifying early retinal changes may be important to prevent progression, which has been noted even after cessation of PPS.<sup><a href="#R7" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R7">7</a></sup> Previous literatures have also identified peripheral retinal involvement with or without macular involvement.<sup><a href="#R3" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R3">3</a>,<a href="#R8" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R8">8</a></sup> Our group speculates that the pathology may not always begin in the macula as four eyes of three patients were noted to have peripapillary autofluorescence (using FAF) and reflectivity (using NIR) pattern abnormalities which spared the macula (grade IB). Considering the phenotypic similarities between peripapillary changes and peripheral changes to those seen in the macula, our group suspects that the RPE-photoreceptor interface is also affected in the peripapillary region and retinal periphery, in a similar manner to that which has been suggested for macular changes.<sup><a href="#R10" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R10">10</a></sup> Nevertheless, cross-sectional scans using SD-OCT may provide more insight into the exact retinal layer the peripapillary changes affect, despite the fact that FAF and NIR images phenotypically mimic those seen in the macular region. In addition, some patients were identified to have marked extra-macular extensions of lesions into the retinal far periphery. As a result, our group believes that PPS toxicity in the eye should be described as a retinal toxicity (retinopathy) rather than macular toxicity (maculopathy) alone. To the best of our knowledge, there are no reports of other structures being affected in the eye aside from the retina. Although there were far peripheral extensions of lesions, the classification did not reflect a progressive increase in the duration of exposure and cumulative dose. It is still unclear why there is a predilection for disease to occur in the macula, but our findings suggest that other retinal regions are also affected. Hydroxychloroquine and tamoxifen retinopathy are also known to cause retinal toxicity and have variable phenotype with dose. Genetic risk factors have been found to be associated with phenotypic variability in these toxicities.<sup><a href="#R11" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R11">11</a>,<a href="#R12" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R12">12</a></sup> Our group hypothesizes that genetic susceptibility may similarly result in phenotypic variability with dose in PPS retinopathy, which is supported by recent genetic association studies.<sup><a href="#R13" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R13">13</a></sup> Furthermore, atrophy did not appear to be dose- and duration-dependent. When compared to the prior grading severity systems<sup><a href="#R3" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R3">3</a>,<a href="#R6" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R6">6</a></sup>, the presence of atrophy within the macula (foveal or extrafoveal) increases the grading severity irrespective of the extent of the lesion. Our classification showed the extent of the lesion with a separate indicator of the presence of atrophy on UWF autofluorescence, which makes the interpretation of an overall lesion relatively uncomplicated. Atrophy was not found to be dose-dependent in our cohort. Again, this may be due to the presence of genetic modifiers of this phenotype. A larger genetic association study will be required to confirm genetic associations of the atrophy phenotype in PPS retinopathy. Perhaps one of the reasons for the development of atrophy was the initial presence of vitelliform deposits that collapsed and progressed to a more severe type of lesion, which is atrophy. It would be valuable to monitor the vitelliform lesions seen in our cohort (2 cases). Another possible reason for the presence of atrophy regardless of classification is an individual’s genetic susceptibility. The development of atrophy with RPE abnormalities may resemble advanced age-related macular degeneration (AMD)<sup><a href="#R14" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R14">14</a></sup>; hence, careful recognition of chronic PPS intake should warrant the clinician of a possibility of toxicity, rather than an atrophic type of advanced AMD, as management will differ between the two groups. One indicator could be the presence or absence of drusen that should be distinguished from RPE changes that occur in PPS toxicity.</p>
<p id="P18">Despite the large number of patients taking PPS seen in the ophthalmology department, the findings are still limited by the relatively small sample size of patients identified with actual toxicity. It is possible that there may be other extra-macular phenotypes. Although we identified several patients with purely peripapillary extra-macular changes, we were unable to identify patients with purely extra-macular changes in the retinal periphery in our cohort. This could possibly be seen in a larger cohort. The 25% proportion of patients with PPS retinopathy seen in our cohort is likely to overestimate the prevalence of PPS retinopathy as the majority of patients referred to our department had visual complaints. Screening in a larger cohort of PPS-exposed patients may provide a more accurate prevalence of PPS retinopathy. Additionally, given the retrospective nature of the study, EHR data may lead to errors in the calculation of cumulative dosing.</p>
<p id="P19">In conclusion, this report widens the phenotypic spectrum of PPS retinopathy and provides a classification system to capture the extent of extra-macular changes in PPS retinopathy. Identification of these extra macular changes, which can be seen on UWF imaging in the setting of prolonged exposure and high cumulative dose of PPS, should alert providers about the potential of retinal toxicity.</p></section><section id="SM1"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Supplementary Material</h2>
<section class="sm xbox font-sm" id="SD1"><div class="caption p"><span>Supplemental Data File</span></div>
<div class="media p" id="d67e338"><div class="caption">
<a href="/articles/instance/13001792/bin/NIHMS1902694-supplement-Supplemental_Data_File.pdf" data-ga-action="click_feat_suppl" class="usa-link">NIHMS1902694-supplement-Supplemental_Data_File.pdf</a><sup> (62.3KB, pdf) </sup>
</div></div></section></section><section id="floats-group1" class="floats-group"><section class="bt xbox font-sm" id="BX1"><h2 class="obj_head">Summary Statement.</h2>
<p id="P41">Pentosan polysulfate sodium (PPS) presents with a wide spectrum of retinal toxicity in addition to macular toxicity. Ultra-wide field imaging may also provide additional clues to retinal toxicity in cases with prolonged exposure to PPS.</p></section></section><section id="S13" class="ack"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Financial support:</h2>
<p id="P20">Foundation Fighting Blindness grant CD-GT-0918-0746-SE (Borooah), Nixon Visions Foundation grant (Borooah), Multimodal Retina Image Alignment and Applications R01EY033847 (Freeman), National Institutes of Health grant DP5OD29610 (Baxter), an unrestricted grant from Research to Prevent Blindness, NY (Freeman), UCSD Vision Research Center Core grant from the National Eye Institute P30EY022589, and unrestricted funds from UCSD Jacobs Retina Center</p></section><section id="fn-group1" class="fn-group"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Footnotes</h2>
